>Shirali AC, Pedrazzoli P, Janus N, et al. Management of chemotherapy including cisplatin in patients with end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis. Nephrol Dial Transplant. 2017;32(5):800&#x2013;7.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Liu Z, Lin Y, et al. Molecular targeted and immune checkpoint therapy for advanced hepatocellular carcinoma. J Exp Clin Cancer Res. 2019;38:447.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1186/s13046-019-1412-8</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">31684985</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">6827249</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Zheng J, Huang A. Hepatocellular carcinoma: signaling pathways and systemic therapy progress. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2025;10:75.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Dong H, Xie F, et al. Combination of immunotherapy and targeted therapy in hepatocellular carcinoma. Curr Treat Options Oncol. 2024;25:12.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1007/s11864-024-01246-9</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Grover SP, Hisada YM, Kasthuri RS, et al. Cancer Therapy-Associated Thrombosis. Arterioscler Thromb Vasc Biol. 2021;41(4):1291&#x2013;305.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1161/ATVBAHA.120.314378</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33567864</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">7990713</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Rhian M Touyz, Sandra MS Herrmann, Joerg Herrmann, et al. Vascular toxicities with VEGF inhibitor therapies&#x2013;focus on hypertension and arterial thrombotic events. J Am Soc Hypertension, 2018;12(6):409&#x2013;425.</Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41850826</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>18</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1349-7235</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>17</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Internal medicine (Tokyo, Japan)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Intern Med</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Combined Hepatocellular-Cholangiocarcinoma Patient Treated with Durvalumab Plus Gemcitabine and Cisplatin: A Case Report.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.2169/internalmedicine.6512-25</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>A 55-year-old man with lower abdominal pain and diarrhea was referred to our hospital. Computed tomography (CT) revealed a hypovascular liver tumor, lymph node/bone metastases, and peritoneal dissemination. Based on a histological analysis of lymph node metastasis, he was diagnosed with combined hepatocellular-cholangiocarcinoma (cHCC-CCA) and received durvalumab plus gemcitabine and cisplatin (Dur/GC). After treatment, the patient developed grade 2 diarrhea and grade 3 thrombocytopenia. CT after one course of Dur/GC demonstrated tumor shrinkage and expanded peritoneal dissemination, suggesting the need for further studies on the efficacy and safety of this therapy for unresectable cHCC-CCA.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kobayashi</LastName><ForeName>Daisuke</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Gastroenterology, Fukushima Medical University School of Medicine, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hayashi</LastName><ForeName>Manabu</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Gastroenterology, Fukushima Medical University School of Medicine, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Takahata</LastName><ForeName>Yosuke</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Gastroenterology, Fukushima Medical University School of Medicine, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><L