TNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Durvalumab</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">atezolizumab</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">bevacizumab</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">hepatocellular carcinoma</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">immunotherapy</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">interleukin-2 receptor</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">interleukin-6</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">major histocompatibility complex-class I</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">programmed cell death-ligand 1</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">regulatory T cells</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">tremelimumab</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">tumor necrosis factor-alpha</Keyword></KeywordList></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>19</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="revised"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>18</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2026</Year><Month>1</Month><Day>5</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>6</Day><Hour>13</Hour><Minute>44</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>2</Month><Day>28</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>41</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>2</Month><Day>27</Day><Hour>21</Hour><Minute>3</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>ppublish</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">41760263</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.21873/anticanres.18049</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">46/3/1545</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41742820</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>05</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>12</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1478-3231</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>46</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Liver international : official journal of the International Association for the Study of the Liver</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Liver Int</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Lymphocyte-Monocyte Ratio Predicts the Survival in Patients With HCC Treated With Durvalumab Plus Tremelimumab.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>e70570</StartPage><MedlinePgn>e70570</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1111/liv.70570</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND AND AIMS" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This multicenter retrospective study in Japan aimed to investigate the prognostic significance of lymphocyte-to-monocyte ratio (LMR) in patients with unresectable hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) treated with durvalumab plus tremelimumab (Dur/Tre).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">A total of 377 patients with HCC and treated with Dur/Tre across 30 institutions in Japan were included in this multicenter study. Time-dependent receiver operating characteristic (ROC) analysis was performed to determine the optimal LMR cut-off value. Hazard ratio (HR) spline curve analysis was used to identify the optimal LMR range for predicting progression-free survival (PFS) and overall survival (OS).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Time-dependent ROC analysis identified an optimal LMR cut-off value of 2.52 for predicting median OS. Multivariate analysis demonstrated that an LMR of &#x2265;&#x2009;2.52 was independently associated with superior PFS (HR: 0.777) and OS (HR: 0.657). The median PFS was 2.6&#x2009;months in patients with an LMR of &lt;&#x2009;2.52, compared with 3.5&#x2009;months in those with an LMR of &#x2265;&#x2009;2.52 (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.022). The median OS was 12.8&#x2009;months in patients with an LMR of &lt;&#x2009;2.52, compared with 23.4&#x2009;months in those with an LMR of &#x2265;&#x2009;2.52 (p&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;0.001). The disease control rate was significantly higher in the high LMR group (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.032). The HR spline curve analysis revealed that an LMR range of approximately 1.8-2.6 represents an optimal cut-off for predicting both PFS and OS.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">LMR is a readily accessible prognostic biomarker for both PFS and OS in patients with unresectable HCC treated with Dur/Tre, and may serve as a practical tool for risk stratification in clinical practice.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2026 John Wiley &amp; Sons A/S. Published by John Wiley &amp; Sons Ltd.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Matono</LastName><ForeName>Tomomitsu</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0001-7114-5464</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Gastroenterology, Harima Himeji General Medical Center, Himeji, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tada</LastName><ForeName>Toshifumi</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-0976-6761</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Gastroenterology, Department of Internal Medicine, Kobe University Graduate School of Medicine, Kobe, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Internal Medicine, Japanese Red Cross Society Himeji Hospital, Himeji, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hiraoka</LastName><ForeName>Atsushi</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-1989-0480</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Gastroenterology, Ehime Prefectural Central Hospital, Matsuyama, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hirooka</LastName><ForeNa